# t/research/memory-forget.test — forgetting is deletion (feature-memory.md). An
# agent drops a memory by DELETING the copy it was handed in in/memory/; the harvest
# diffs this run's provisioned set against the survivors and records a forget. The
# diff is per-name: a sibling memory the agent kept is untouched.

send allow-sender { address kasi@decode.ee }

# Two facts käsi already knows (seeded directly, as the /memory page would).
memory write reply-style   [fixture memory/reply-style.md]
memory write owner-banking [fixture memory/owner-banking.md]

# Task 1 is handed both.
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "draft"
    body    "draft a reply to the vendor about the overdue invoice"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent
task 1 input memory/reply-style.md   matches "*Lead with the answer*"
task 1 input memory/owner-banking.md matches "*Handelsbanken*"

# During the task the agent decides the reply-style note no longer applies and
# deletes the copy it was given — that deletion is the whole forget gesture. It
# keeps owner-banking.
agent {
    out reply.txt "Drafted the reply."
    del in/memory/reply-style.md
}
task 1 status is awaiting-user

# owner-banking survives in the collection; reply-style was forgotten (a per-name
# diff, not wholesale).
memory owner-banking matches "*Wise*"

# A brand-new task is handed only what remains — owner-banking, never the forgotten
# reply-style. The inputs set is the negative proof: no memory/reply-style.md.
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "pay this"
    body    "pay the attached invoice"
}
task 2 status is awaiting-agent
task 2 input memory/owner-banking.md matches "*Handelsbanken*"
task 2 inputs are {MEMORY.md body.txt memory/owner-banking.md}
